title: Grateful Dead Live at Alumni Stadium - University of Massachusetts on 1979-05-12
lineage: MAC > Nakamichi DR-1 > Benchmark ADC-1 > AES > Sound Devices 722 > WAV

reviews.review_text:
good show This was the first show I saw with Brett, after many shows with Donna and Keith. It took a little time to get used to the "new sound." Some of our group were set to not like it, but brett's keyboards made the sound richer or fuller, and we really enjoyed the change.
The weather looked like it was going to pour all day... damp and not pleasant.  felt bad for the UMass kids since it was their spring fest, and the weather wasn't very "springy."
It was a great selection of tunes, with a stellar terrapin

Ahmerst- University of Massachusetts We were seniors in High school from Long Island, New York. The five of us drove my "71 Volkswagon to see the DEAD. Whoow sooo smoky... Got here safe and early. Patti Smith opened the show and the Dead Heads were a bit removed from her powerful show but you know it was 79 and the majority was there to see the DEAD. 
The Dead opened with a Rockin JACK STRAW. But it was my first show after seeing them through the 70's with Kieth and Donna and Bret was dissapointing. But Jerry, Bob,Phil,Bill,and Mickey prevailed. The show was spirited and when the biker rode up the Football Field to the front of the stage on his Harley it was really unforgetable to this day 31 years later. 
Anything Jerry did will last forever.

My First Dead Show I was a WMass HS Jr and spent the weekend at UMass   I think I saw a great first show and it was a wide-eyed experience for a 16 + year old.  I will always remember the following songs from that show:  jack Straw, Tennessee Jed, Terrapin, Good Lovin, Not Fade Away and Saturday Night.  The bikers, semi nude girls, and top-of-the-wall-walkers are also etched into my mind :)

UMass Spring Bash! I attended this show with my first ever boyfriend and I introduced him to my best friend from HS that day. We did some double barrel and had a wonderful time. It was the convolution of punk, R&R and Disco so The Ramones, P Smith and the newly discoed Dead had a day of it.
